  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>Another thing that could be done along these lines is have three levels in which
you can take the missions: 'easy', 'medium' and 'hard'.

If you choose the easy level, you'll get an explanation and after the
explanation, the exact command that you have to type.

If you choose the medium level, you'll get only the explanation, and you have to
do something (like click or hover), to see the 'easy' section.

If you choose the hard level, you'll only get the stuff that you have to do,
without explanations, and you have to do something in order to see first the
'medium' section and then, if you still want more help, the 'easy' section.

I know it's not a trivial change at all, but I think they might be more fun like
this.

Thanks for rocking missions!</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
  <tr>
   <th><a href="msg2316">msg2316 (view)</a></th>
   <th>Author: margamanterola</th>
   <th>Date: 2011-08-17.14:21:17</th>
   <th>
    
   </th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>My comments are based on the "tar" mission, I'm not sure how the rest are
structured, but I suspect they are similar.

The introduction to the subject is pretty short, and the person that has to
complete the mission is going to be quite lost without the "hints".  The "hints"
on the other hand, are so straight forward that they don't allow much thought
and processing, they just have to type a command and see what it does.

From my point of view, it'd be better to allow another level of hints, with a
couple of links to follow, or suggested google searches that will turn up the
correct results.

Another possibility would be to include this information as an additional page,
as already suggested in <a href="http://openhatch.org/bugs/issue535,">http://openhatch.org/bugs/issue535,</a> however, I do think
that it is educational for people to have to find the info and process it by
themselves, just that maybe they need a bit more orientation about how to find it.

PS: Thanks for such an awesome idea turned into reality!</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
